reviewText: The 3 Fast Miles is one of my favorite workouts and Fast Start 1 & 2 Miles are perfect if you need a shorter day or if you've taken time off and need to work back up to longer workouts. This is classic Leslie with a group of walkers, many originals. It loses a star based solely on the fact that at one point in the 3 mile, she asks Mary Kay to lead, but Mary Kay doesn't have a mike! You can't hear a word she says! Oops!
summary: 3 Miles is one of my favorite workouts!

reviewText: I was pleasantly surprised at this DVD. I have Leslie's Walk Away the Pounds, and like it so I bought the Walk Slim series. The 'Fast Start' 1&2 miles has some jogging, and it moves fairly quickly. My favorite is the 3 Fast Miles mile which has more variation; no jogging, but it does have some dancing which gets me moving.  Leslie looks great, and as always, her sincerity comes across to you. I was definitely sweating and felt great afterward. I would recommend this to anyone that wants a great workout that is easy on the joints.
summary: Good music, good variety. You can't miss !

reviewText: So far, I have only done the 3-mile workout- but what a workout this is!  Make no mistake, it's pretty much the same Leslie we're all used to, so don't expect any surprising new moves.  However, one of the things I really like about this DVD is that she jumps right in at the beginning and starts the program without the explanations of what the steps are- it seems as if she expects that by the time you're doing a 3-mile workout, you know what a tap-out or a kickback is.  Also, the pace seems to be elevated in this one- the warm-up is more brisk than I've come to expect in Leslie's videos.  The one, straight-up GOOFY thing in this video comes towards the end when she has Mary Kay lead the exercises for a few minutes, but seemed to have forgotten that MK isn't miked.  And when I say not miked, I mean you cannot hear a word she's saying, and are reduced to lip-reading.  Granted that it doesn't take a rocket scientist to figure out what she wants you to do, but it seemed like a really strange thing to leave on the finished DVD.  This aside, I really like this video and plan to put it in regular rotation among my other Leslie favorites.
